<div class="container content">
  <h3>Waveform recognition performance</h3>
  <p class="nice-wrap">
    A2EPG was subjected to an extensive performance analysis showing a
    substantial recognition effectiveness for the studied EPG waveforms (Np, C,
    pd, G and E1) at a low computational cost for records of medium-to-high
    quality.
  </p>
  <p class="nice-wrap">
    Specifications on the effectiveness assessment and the results
    can be found in the corresponding journal article entitled <em>"A2EPG: A new
    software for the analysis of electrical penetration graphs to study plant
    probing behaviour of hemipteran insects"</em>, which is available
    <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.compag.2015.02.005">here</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>Benchmark tools</h3>
  <p class="nice-wrap">
    Several software routines were written to deal with the comparison between
    manual inspection and the automatic scan results. Such utilities were packed
    into a single script written in Python, <code>a2epg_post_analysis.py</code>,
    that takes one or more pairs of mark files (<code>.csv</code> files), and
    it calculates all the metrics used in the publication mentioned above.
  </p>
  <p class="nice-wrap">
    You need at least Python 3.4 and
    <a href="http://matplotlib.org">matplotlib</a> plotting library if you wish
    to generate confusion matrix graphs (optional). The script should be
    executed as follows:
  </p>
  <pre class="pre-scrollable">
<span style="color: red;">$ python a2epg_post_analysis.py Ap1-haba-auto.csv Ap1-haba-manual.csv</span>
Comparing Ap1-haba... done.

